# LOAD GENERIC FUNCTIONS
# Function 2 checks if a main table_row on webpage extract s an athletic entry
def is_athlete_entryb(table_row):
    row_cells = table_row.findAll("td")
    try:
        testAthid=str(row_cells[6].a)[40:50].replace('"','').replace('>','').replace(' ','')
        
    except IndexError:
        testAthid=""
    
    return (len(row_cells) == 14 and len(testAthid) != 0)

# Function 1 to go through lines of html of ranking web page to get athlete id rows 
def get_all_athletesb(html_soup,EventH1,Sex1,htmlstring1b):
    #athletes = []
    all_rows_in_html_page = html_soup.findAll("tr")
    for table_row in all_rows_in_html_page:
 
    # Run is_athlete_entryb to check if main table row is athletic entry, if yes, extract fields and append to entry table
        if is_athlete_entryb(table_row):
            row_cells = table_row.findAll("td")
            athlete_entry = {
                #"cohort": filestring
                "MEvent": EventH1,
                "Sex": Sex1,
                "Cohort":htmlstring1b,
                "rank": row_cells[0].text,
                "perf": row_cells[1].text,
                "ws": row_cells[3].text,
                "pbtime": row_cells[4].text,
                "pbflag": row_cells[5].text,
                "name": row_cells[6].text,
                "yeargrp": row_cells[8].text,
                "athleteid": str(row_cells[6].a)[42:49].replace('"','').replace('>','').replace(' ','').replace('t','').replace('a',''),
                "venue": row_cells[11].text.replace(',',''), 
                #"date": row_cells[12].text.replace(" ", "/"),
                "date": pd.to_datetime(row_cells[12].text.replace(" ", "/"), format='%d/%b/%y'),
                #"date": row_cells[12].text,
            }
            athletes.append(athlete_entry)
    return athletes

# Function 6 - Determines if a table_row is an athlete entry
def is_athlete_times_entryd(table_row, Sex2):
    row_cells = table_row.findAll("td")
    event_header = row_cells[0].text
    EventCheck1=(event_header =='200' and Sex2=='W')
    EventCheck2=(event_header =="1500" and Sex2=='M')
    return (len(row_cells) == 12 and (EventCheck1 or EventCheck2))

B- Feature Engineering - Relative Age Effect- is birth month significant? Could it be an additional feature?¶

Code Comment: The birth month of the top 200 athletes in the 2006 U13 cohort was extracted from the Date of Birth field and summarised using a "countif" formuala. This was repeated for the same cohort for years through to 2018. Results are plotted in excel and shown below.

Observations:

  • The percentage of total births per month in England and Wales from 1995 to 2014 varies between 8.72% in July and 7.62% in February. (Data Source: Office for National Statistics). Monthly births do not vary much but there is a seasonal trend with most births in July and the following 3 months.
  • But the distribution of top athlete births varies considerably. The chart below shows the distribution of birth months for age groups. For example, the 2013-U13 cohort has 25% were born in September and October whilst just 5% were born in July and August.
  • September is a “high” month for U13 and U15.
  • There is also a peak in in November and December
  • Far fewer athletes are born in July.
  • The above variation declines for the older age groups.
  • There is also less variation in a similar chart for older All-Time athletes though July appears very low.
  • These results appear to show the "Relative Age Effect" previously noted in Canadian Hockey Teams and other sports.

Feature Engineering:

  • I decided NOT to include "Relative Age" as an extra feature given project timetable and the fact that it appeared less significant as age increased. Further discussion in report.

5-Create Athlete entries file for curve fitting¶

5a-Note manual step if importing additional events measured in minutes¶

Data Wrangling:

  • Entries file exported to excel to allow additional conversion formula.
    Manual step: Add in PERF1N formula below in excel and rename AllEntriesDoB1.xlsx to AllEntriesDoB2.xlsx and save.
    NB: This fix converts minute times and second times in same field into seconds. It allows the code to extract additional sports to be extracted with diffrent time formats. Eg currently Womens 200m AND Mens 1500m events are downloaded to allow comparison between events and sexes.
    The formula is '=IF(D2=200,VALUE(D2=200,VALUE(G2),(LEFT(G2,(FIND(":",G2,(FIND(":",G2,1)-1))*60)+VALUE(MID(G2,FIND(":",G2,FIND(":",G2,1)+1,20)))' as fix couldn't be found in Python at time.

Code Comment:

  • Calculate EventAge for each event by subtracting Event Data from Dob.
  • Create new field to make a 'numeric' age field. Divide numeric age to create a year-decimal value.
  • Calculate new Speed field.

5-Create Athlete entries file for curve fitting¶

5b- Create extra numeric fields to enrich entries table, select best performance per Year-Month for each athlete¶

Observations:

  • It was noted that athlete results could be very noisy over short periods of time. This is explained that larger competitions have several heats in the days before a final which are also recorded. The objective for an athlete is to do just enough to get through the heat without risking exhaustion or injury.
    It was decided to filter results to take the best result for each Year-Month period.
  • For comparison, in Berthelot's paper, the best result PER YEAR was taken. On average 6.2 (SD 1.36) performance points per athlete were analysed (-see PDF for ref)

Code Comment:

  • Select best performance per Year-Month for each athlete
  • Create separate table to identify maximum and minimum event ages
  • Create new numeric fields for various date format fields to allow calculations
  • Add flags to identify which events to be included in different prediction scenarios.

  • The shape is consistent with Moore's formula (detailed in Berthelot's paper- see PDF for ref): P(t)=a(1−ebt)+c(1−edt)P(t)=a(1−ebt)+c(1−edt)
    Speed is a function of age determined by 2 expoential factors. One factor increases whilst the other factor decreases with time. Note there are 4 constants in formula.
  • A plot for the current UK record holder, Dina Asher-Smith, is also highlighted. As can be seen in the chart, until 19 years she was in the middle of this cohort. But the gradient of her progress before 19 was relatively steep. This is consistent with the rationale for following a machine learning approach.

8-Curve-fitting¶

8a- Run main Curve-fitting cycle¶

Code Comment:

  • Cell below runs 3 scenarios to derive 3 sets of curve coefficient constants. The scenarios are:
    • using all event data up until 2018 PB,
    • using data up to 2 years prior to PB,
    • only using data up to 4 years prior to PB.
  • Constants "c", "c2", "c4" give a theoretical maximum speed base on data up to 2018, 2016, and 2014.
  • Predicted PBs are then recalculated using the new formulae. In code below these are PBP (PB Predicted), PBP2, PBP4
  • For each predicted line R^2, the coefficient of determination is also calculated.
  • A summary graph showing actual results and 3 prediction lines are plotted for each athlete.
  • Data is output ina table to allow further summary.

Return to Index

Scope Change: In first curve-fitting iterations, an attempt was made to derive the constants for the full Moores formula:
P(t)=a(1−ebt)+c(1−edt)P(t)=a(1−ebt)+c(1−edt)
However, as explained in the EDA, there is very little data for athletes competing after attaining their PBs and the curve-fitting function could NOT solve for the constants in the decreasing exponential component. As there was not enough data to model athelete speed over a full lifetime, I decided to use an approximated formula:
P(t)=a(1−ebt)P(t)=a(1−ebt)
...and only model and use event data up to an athlete's current PB event. In this equation "a" gives a theoretical maximum speed. This might be useful for ranking but according to Moore's formula would not be attained. Additionally, I changed my assessment objective. Originally I planned to predicted actual PB speeds and compare those to actuals. After simplifying the model but I decided I should just predict rankings as actual predicted speeds might be inaccurate. Rankings would be compared using data visualisation and calculating a Spearman's Coefficient for each scenario ranking compared to actual ranking. See below and PDF Report.
WARNING: LATE DISCOVERED BUG! The modified test objective was to run curve-fit the 2014 Top-50 ranked athletes and predict their 2018 ranking according toa predicted PB. When this run results were produced for 34 athletes which were then used for further analysis. 3 of these athletes had already been removed for formating and date of birth verification issues. Code was written to filter out athletes with too few races for curve-fitting to run and it was initially assumed that the remaining 13 athletes were excluded from analysis for this reason. Just before report submission I reviewed this explanation as I thought it unlikley that all 13 athletes in a top 50 ranking would have too few event points. I checked 2 excluded athletes and have found that they did have enough races in the data for curve fitting. I think that their exclusion arose when I changed the scope and decided to only use data up to their PB date. One of the filter rules checks to see if there are enough events for curve fitting 4 years prior to her PB. Some of the athletes with a PB close to 2014 may not have had enough race events pre-2010 and were filtered out for curve-fitting. Some logic re-writing is required however simply removing this rule and re-running now will mean that post-PB data will included for some athletes which will invalidate my assumptions for modifying Moore's formula.

# define function for fitting
def bpm(t,c0,c1):
    #return c0+c1*t-c2*np.exp(-c3*t)
    #return c0*(1-np.exp(c1*t))+c2*(1-np.exp(c3*t))
    return c0*(1-np.exp(c1*t))

for i in Athlist.index.values:

    t = Entriesb['EventAgeYN'].values
    ym = Entriesb['Speed'].values

    Entriesc=Entriesb[Entriesb.EvPrePB2Y_x == 1]
    
    t2= Entriesc['EventAgeYN'].values
    ym2= Entriesc['Speed'].values
    
     #makes vectors based on 4 yrs before PB
    Entriesd=Entriesb[Entriesb.EvPrePB4Y_x == 1]
    
    t4= Entriesd['EventAgeYN'].values
    ym4= Entriesd['Speed'].values
      
    
    #find optimal parameters
    p0 = [8,-0.15]        # initial guesses
    
    # calculate curve fit 1                  
    c,cov = curve_fit(bpm,t,ym,p0)  # fit model
    
    ca=c[0]
    cb=c[1]
    PBP=c[0]-c[0]*np.exp(c[1]*PBEventAgeYN)
 
    # calculate prediction 1
    yp = bpm(t,c[0],c[1])
    # calculate r^2
    R2_score= r2_score(ym,yp)
   
    # calculate curve fit 2
    c2,cov2 = curve_fit(bpm,t2,ym2,p0)  # fit model
    
    ca2=c2[0]
    cb2=c2[1]
    PBP2=c2[0]-c2[0]*np.exp(c2[1]*PBEventAgeYN)
 
    # calculate prediction2
    yp2 = bpm(t,c2[0],c2[1])
    # calculate r^2

    yp3=bpm(t2,c2[0],c2[1]) 
    
    # calculate curve fit 4
    c4,cov4 = curve_fit(bpm,t4,ym4,p0)  # fit model
    
    ca4=c4[0]
    cb4=c4[1]
    PBP4=c4[0]-c4[0]*np.exp(c4[1]*PBEventAgeYN)
 
    # calculate prediction 4
    yp4 = bpm(t,c4[0],c4[1])
    # calculate r^2
    R2_score4= r2_score(ym,yp4)
    
    yp5=bpm(t4,c4[0],c4[1])

E-Curvefitting Review¶

Code Comment:

  • The above run of plots in the notebook window and the example below (Dina Asher-Smith) comprises the 2014 Top 50 200m Women. The curves were also plotted against actual results for a visual summary. The estimated constants for each scenario were appended to a table.
  • As per the objective curve fitting was run under 3 scenarios to calculated predicted rankings for 2018 and compare them to actual rankings.
  • Data was exported to an excel file ("Ath_curves2014.xlsx") to produce a summary table below and calculate Spearman's Coefficients.

Observations:

  • The original plan test plan was to take the 2014 Top-50 ranked athletes and predict their 2018 ranking. However, the code only ran curve-fitting for 34 athletes - see above for details of the Bug.
  • See Dina Asher-Smith example below. The red dots indicate actual race data. The three lines have been plotted as follows:
    • "Predicted" green line is the line of best fit using data up to 2018
    • "Predicted2" is the blue line based on data up to 2 years before the athlete's PB. The dotted blue line is an extrapolation of the line to their actual PB.
    • "Predicted4" is the yellow line based on data up to 2 years before the athlete's PB. The dotted line is an extrapolation of the line to their actual PB.
  • The example below shows a close correlation of the lines, so data upto 2014 was a good predictor of a 2018 PB. Not all examples were this close - review the other curves and R^2 values in the notebook window above.
  • Predictions made with data up to 2016 were generally much closer than thos emade from data up to 2014. This is quantified in Spearman Correlation analysis below.

F-Spearman Correlation of Predicted-to-Actual Rankings¶

Code Comment:

  • Data was exported to an excel file ("Ath_curves2014.xlsx") to produce a summary table below and calculate Spearman's Coefficients.

Observations:

  • The table below shows visually by colour how close the 3 prediction scenarios were to actual rankings.
  • Spearman's rank correlation coefficient were as follows:
    • Predicted ranking for 2018 using data up to 2018: 0.9410
    • Predicted ranking for 2018 using data up to 2016: 0.8191
    • Predicted ranking for 2018 using data up to 2014: 0.4383
  • Prediction accuracy improves the over shorter time spans.
  • Prediction accuracy on 2014 data is higher for older athletes with more event data.
  • Larger errors were made for the 2 athletes ranked 5 and 31 in 2018. They are both young and so the 2014 predictions was based on the smaller volume of data available when they were only 14 and 15 years old.

        #return c0+c1*t-c2*np.exp(-c3*t)
        #return c0*(1-np.exp(c1*t))+c2*(1-np.exp(c3*t))
    return c0*(1-np.exp(c1*t))
